    {"problem": "Explain how decorators work in Python. Write a decorator that measures function execution time.",
     "reasoning": "A decorator is a function that takes another function as input, wraps its behavior, and returns a new function. The @decorator syntax is syntactic sugar for func = decorator(func). To preserve the original function's metadata (name, docstring), use functools.wraps. For a timer decorator: inside the wrapper, record time before calling the function, call it, record time after, print the difference, and return the result. Decorators are commonly used for logging, access control, caching, and instrumentation. They demonstrate Python's first-class function support and closure mechanism.",
     "code": "import time\nfrom functools import wraps\n\ndef timer(func):\n    @wraps(func)\n    def wrapper(*args, **kwargs):\n        start = time.perf_counter()\n        result = func(*args, **kwargs)\n        elapsed = time.perf_counter() - start\n        print(f'{func.__name__} took {elapsed:.4f}s')\n        return result\n    return wrapper\n\n@timer\ndef slow_function():\n    sum(range(10**6))"},

    {"problem": "What is the GIL in Python and how does it affect threading? When are threads useful despite the GIL?",
     "reasoning": "The Global Interpreter Lock (GIL) is a mutex in CPython that prevents multiple threads from executing Python bytecode simultaneously. This means CPU-bound multithreaded programs won't see speedup on multi-core systems — only one thread runs at a time. However, threads ARE useful for I/O-bound tasks: when one thread is waiting for network/disk I/O, it releases the GIL, allowing other threads to run. For CPU-bound parallelism, use multiprocessing (separate processes with separate GILs) instead of threading. Alternative: use asyncio for I/O concurrency without threads, or use C extensions (NumPy, Cython) that release the GIL during long operations.",
     "code": "import threading, time\n\n# I/O-bound: threads help (GIL released during I/O wait)\ndef fetch_url(url):\n    import requests\n    requests.get(url)  # releases GIL while waiting\n\n# CPU-bound: threads DON'T help (GIL held)\ndef count(n):\n    while n > 0:\n        n -= 1  # pure Python, holds GIL\n\n# use multiprocessing instead:\nfrom multiprocessing import Pool\nwith Pool() as p:\n    p.map(count, [10**7, 10**7])  # runs on multiple cores"},

