    # ── DATA STRUCTURES ──
    {"problem": "Implement a Least Recently Used (LRU) cache with O(1) get and put operations. The cache has a fixed capacity and evicts the least recently used item when full.",
     "reasoning": "Use a doubly linked list combined with a hash map. The list maintains items in order of use: the most recently used item is at the head, and the least recently used is at the tail. The hash map provides O(1) lookup from key to list node. On get: if key exists, move its node to the head (remove from current position, add to head), return value. On put: if key exists, update value and move to head. If key is new and at capacity, evict the tail node (last item in list) and remove it from the hash map, then insert the new node at the head. Use dummy head and tail nodes to simplify boundary operations.",
     "code": "class Node:\n    def __init__(self, key=0, val=0):\n        self.key, self.val = key, val\n        self.prev = self.next = None\n\nclass LRUCache:\n    def __init__(self, cap):\n        self.cap = cap\n        self.map = {}\n        self.head = Node()\n        self.tail = Node()\n        self.head.next = self.tail\n        self.tail.prev = self.head\n    def _remove(self, n):\n        n.prev.next = n.next\n        n.next.prev = n.prev\n    def _add_to_head(self, n):\n        n.next = self.head.next\n        n.prev = self.head\n        self.head.next.prev = n\n        self.head.next = n\n    def get(self, key):\n        if key not in self.map:\n            return -1\n        n = self.map[key]\n        self._remove(n)\n        self._add_to_head(n)\n        return n.val\n    def put(self, key, val):\n        if key in self.map:\n            n = self.map[key]\n            self._remove(n)\n            n.val = val\n            self._add_to_head(n)\n            return\n        if len(self.map) >= self.cap:\n            lru = self.tail.prev\n            self._remove(lru)\n            del self.map[lru.key]\n        n = Node(key, val)\n        self.map[key] = n\n        self._add_to_head(n)"},

    {"problem": "Design a data structure that supports insert, delete, and getRandom in O(1) average time. All operations should be equally likely for getRandom.",
     "reasoning": "Use a dynamic array (list) for O(1) index access plus a hash map from value to its index in the array. Insert: append value to the array, store (value -> index) in the map. Delete: get the index of the value from the map, swap it with the last element in the array (this avoids the O(n) shift from deleting in the middle), update the map entry for the swapped element, then pop the last element and remove the value from the map. getRandom: generate a random index in [0, size-1] and return array[index]. The swap-with-last trick is essential for O(1) deletion while maintaining the array structure.",
     "code": "import random\n\nclass RandomizedSet:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.arr = []\n        self.pos = {}\n    def insert(self, val):\n        if val in self.pos:\n            return False\n        self.pos[val] = len(self.arr)\n        self.arr.append(val)\n        return True\n    def remove(self, val):\n        if val not in self.pos:\n            return False\n        i = self.pos[val]\n        last = self.arr[-1]\n        self.arr[i] = last\n        self.pos[last] = i\n        self.arr.pop()\n        del self.pos[val]\n        return True\n    def getRandom(self):\n        return random.choice(self.arr)"},

