    {"problem": "Given an array where every element appears twice except for one, find the single element. Solve in O(n) time and O(1) space.",
     "reasoning": "XOR all numbers together. XOR is commutative and associative, and a XOR a = 0, a XOR 0 = a. Since each duplicate pair XORs to 0, all duplicates cancel out, leaving the single element that appears once. Example: [2,1,2] -> 2 XOR 1 XOR 2 = (2 XOR 2) XOR 1 = 0 XOR 1 = 1. This works because XOR is its own inverse. O(n) time, O(1) space. This is the classic bit manipulation trick that exploits the algebraic properties of XOR. It works for finding a single element when all others appear an even number of times.",
     "code": "def single_number(nums):\n    res = 0\n    for n in nums:\n        res ^= n\n    return res\n# single_number([4,1,2,1,2]) = 4"},

    {"problem": "Count the number of 1 bits in an integer (Hamming weight). Solve in O(number of 1s) time.",
     "reasoning": "Brian Kernighan's algorithm: repeatedly clear the least significant set bit using n = n & (n-1). The operation n-1 flips all bits after the rightmost 1, so n & (n-1) clears that rightmost 1. Count how many iterations until n becomes 0. This is more efficient than checking every bit when the number has few 1-bits. For example, n=12 (1100): 12&11=8 (1000), 8&7=0. Count=2, which is correct (12 has two 1-bits). O(k) where k is the number of 1-bits, vs O(32) for brute force. For very sparse numbers, this is significantly faster.",
     "code": "def hamming_weight(n):\n    count = 0\n    while n:\n        n &= n - 1\n        count += 1\n    return count\n# hamming_weight(11) = 3 (1011 has three 1s)"},

