    {"problem": "Explain the Producer-Consumer pattern and implement it with a bounded buffer using threading primitives.",
     "reasoning": "Producers generate data and put it into a shared buffer. Consumers take data from the buffer and process it. The buffer has a fixed capacity. Two problems arise: the buffer can become full (producers must wait), or empty (consumers must wait). Multiple threads accessing the buffer simultaneously causes race conditions. Solution: use a Condition variable. The condition wraps a lock and provides wait() and notify() methods. Producers wait for 'not full', add item, then notify 'not empty'. Consumers wait for 'not empty', remove item, then notify 'not full'. In Python, queue.Queue handles all this internally, but implementing it manually demonstrates thread synchronization concepts.",
     "code": "from threading import Condition, Thread\nfrom collections import deque\n\nclass BoundedBuffer:\n    def __init__(self, cap):\n        self.buf = deque()\n        self.cap = cap\n        self.cv = Condition()\n    def put(self, item):\n        with self.cv:\n            while len(self.buf) >= self.cap:\n                self.cv.wait()\n            self.buf.append(item)\n            self.cv.notify_all()\n    def get(self):\n        with self.cv:\n            while not self.buf:\n                self.cv.wait()\n            item = self.buf.popleft()\n            self.cv.notify_all()\n            return item"},

