    {"problem": "Implement binary search on a sorted array. Return the index of the target or -1 if not found.",
     "reasoning": "Binary search repeatedly divides the search space in half. Maintain left and right pointers. At each step, compute mid = (l+r)//2. If arr[mid] equals target, return mid. If target < arr[mid], search left half (r = mid-1). If target > arr[mid], search right half (l = mid+1). Continue until l > r (not found). O(log n) time, O(1) space. Binary search requires a sorted array. For finding insertion points, use bisect_left (first position where target could be inserted) and bisect_right (last position + 1). The invariant: target must be in [l, r], and this interval halves each iteration.",
     "code": "def binary_search(arr, target):\n    l, r = 0, len(arr) - 1\n    while l <= r:\n        mid = (l + r) // 2\n        if arr[mid] == target:\n            return mid\n        elif arr[mid] < target:\n            l = mid + 1\n        else:\n            r = mid - 1\n    return -1\n\n# binary_search([1,3,5,7,9], 5) = 2"},

    {"problem": "Given an unsorted array of n numbers in range 1 to n, one number is missing. Find it in O(n) time and O(1) space.",
     "reasoning": "Since the numbers are in range 1..n and exactly one is missing, the expected sum is n*(n+1)/2. Compute the actual sum of the array. The missing number is expected_sum - actual_sum. This uses O(n) time and O(1) space. However, for very large n, the sum might overflow. Alternative: XOR approach. XOR all numbers 1..n and XOR with all array elements. Pairs cancel out, leaving the missing number. XOR avoids overflow: (1^2^...^n) ^ (arr[0]^arr[1]^...^arr[n-2]) = missing number. Both approaches work but XOR is safer for large n.",
     "code": "def find_missing(nums):\n    n = len(nums) + 1\n    xor_all = 0\n    for i in range(1, n + 1):\n        xor_all ^= i\n    for x in nums:\n        xor_all ^= x\n    return xor_all\n\n# find_missing([1,2,4,5]) = 3"},

    # ── SORTING ──
    {"problem": "Implement merge sort on an array. Explain why it's O(n log n) and stable.",
     "reasoning": "Merge sort: divide the array into halves, recursively sort each half, then merge the sorted halves. The merge step uses two pointers to compare elements from each half and build the result in sorted order. Time complexity: the array is divided log n times (halving), and each level merges n elements total, so O(n log n) in all cases. It's stable because when two elements are equal, the one from the left half comes first (due to the merge step using <=). Space: O(n) auxiliary for the temporary array during merge. Unlike quicksort, merge sort guarantees O(n log n) but uses more space.",
     "code": "def merge_sort(arr):\n    if len(arr) <= 1:\n        return arr\n    mid = len(arr) // 2\n    left = merge_sort(arr[:mid])\n    right = merge_sort(arr[mid:])\n    merged = []\n    i = j = 0\n    while i < len(left) and j < len(right):\n        if left[i] <= right[j]:\n            merged.append(left[i])\n            i += 1\n        else:\n            merged.append(right[j])\n            j += 1\n    merged.extend(left[i:])\n    merged.extend(right[j:])\n    return merged\n\n# merge_sort([3,1,4,1,5,9]) = [1,1,3,4,5,9]"},

    {"problem": "Implement quicksort with in-place partitioning. Explain pivot selection strategies.",
     "reasoning": "Quicksort: pick a pivot, partition the array so elements <= pivot are on the left and > pivot are on the right. Then recursively sort the left and right partitions. The partition step uses the Lomuto scheme (single pass) or Hoare scheme (two pointers). Pivot selection matters: always-pick-first degrades to O(n^2) on sorted arrays. Better strategies: random pivot (average O(n log n)), median-of-three (pick median of first, middle, last), or introspective sort (switch to heapsort if recursion depth exceeds log n). Quicksort is in-place (O(log n) stack space) and usually faster than merge sort in practice due to cache behavior, but it's unstable.",
     "code": "import random\n\ndef quicksort(arr, l=0, r=None):\n    if r is None:\n        r = len(arr) - 1\n    if l >= r:\n        return\n    p = random.randint(l, r)\n    arr[p], arr[r] = arr[r], arr[p]\n    i = l\n    for j in range(l, r):\n        if arr[j] <= arr[r]:\n            arr[i], arr[j] = arr[j], arr[i]\n            i += 1\n    arr[i], arr[r] = arr[r], arr[i]\n    quicksort(arr, l, i-1)\n    quicksort(arr, i+1, r)\n    return arr"},

