    {"problem": "Explain the N+1 query problem in ORMs (like SQLAlchemy or Django ORM) and how to solve it.",
     "reasoning": "The N+1 problem: fetching a list of N parent records (1 query), then accessing a related field for each parent (N queries). Example: posts = Post.query.all(); for p in posts: print(p.author.name) — this runs 1 query for posts + N queries for authors = N+1 queries. This destroys performance with large N. Solutions: eager loading (use JOIN in the initial query with .joinedload() in SQLAlchemy or select_related() in Django), batch loading (use .subqueryload() or prefetch_related() for many-to-many), or use DataLoader pattern (batch + cache per request). The core principle: batch related data retrieval into fewer queries, ideally just 2 (one for parents, one for all related children).",
     "code": "# SQLAlchemy: N+1 (BAD)\n# posts = session.query(Post).all()\n# for p in posts:\n#     print(p.author.name)  # N queries!\n\n# Solution with eager loading (GOOD)\nfrom sqlalchemy.orm import joinedload\nposts = session.query(Post).options(joinedload(Post.author)).all()\n# Now 1 query with JOIN instead of N+1\n\n# Django equivalent:\n# posts = Post.objects.select_related('author').all()"},

    {"problem": "What is a database index (B+ tree) and when does it help or hurt performance?",
     "reasoning": "A B+ tree index stores a sorted copy of the indexed column(s) with pointers to rows. Lookups are O(log n) instead of O(n) full table scan. Each node holds many keys (high branching factor), so the tree is short (typically 3-4 levels even for millions of rows). Leaf nodes are linked for efficient range scans. Indexes help: WHERE, JOIN, ORDER BY, and MIN/MAX queries on indexed columns. They HURT: INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE (index must be maintained), and they use disk space. Composite indexes (multiple columns) support index-only scans and work for prefix queries. Don't index columns with low cardinality (like boolean) — the index isn't selective enough to be useful.",
     "code": "# Good candidates for indexes:\n# - Foreign keys (frequently joined)\n# - Columns used in WHERE with high selectivity\n# - Columns used in ORDER BY\n# - Columns used in range queries\n#\n# CREATE INDEX idx_user_email ON users(email);\n# CREATE INDEX idx_order_user_date ON orders(user_id, created_at);"},

