    {"problem": "Explain the TCP three-way handshake. Why is it needed and what happens if a step fails?",
     "reasoning": "TCP three-way handshake establishes a reliable connection. Step 1 (SYN): Client sends SYN with initial sequence number x. Step 2 (SYN-ACK): Server responds with SYN-ACK, its own seq=y, and ack=x+1 (confirming receipt of SYN). Step 3 (ACK): Client sends ACK with seq=x+1 and ack=y+1. This establishes bidirectional communication and synchronizes sequence numbers for reliable data transfer. If SYN is lost: client retransmits after timeout. If SYN-ACK is lost: client retransmits SYN. If ACK is lost: server still considers the connection open (it received the SYN) and waits for data; client considers it open (it received SYN-ACK). The server may retransmit SYN-ACK if it doesn't receive data. Without the handshake, old duplicate packets could create spurious connections or corrupt data streams.",
     "code": "# TCP 3-way handshake:\n# Client -> Server: SYN (seq=x)\n# Server -> Client: SYN-ACK (seq=y, ack=x+1)\n# Client -> Server: ACK (seq=x+1, ack=y+1)\n#\n# State transitions:\n# CLOSED -> SYN_SENT -> ESTABLISHED (client)\n# LISTEN -> SYN_RCVD -> ESTABLISHED (server)"},

