    {"problem": "Explain virtual memory and page replacement. Compare LRU, FIFO, and Optimal page replacement algorithms.",
     "reasoning": "Virtual memory maps virtual addresses to physical memory using page tables. When a page not in physical memory is accessed, a page fault occurs and the OS loads it from disk. If physical memory is full, a page must be evicted. Page replacement algorithms: FIFO (queue, evict oldest) is simple but can evict frequently used pages and suffers from Belady's anomaly (more frames can cause MORE page faults). LRU (evict least recently used) exploits temporal locality — recently accessed pages are likely accessed again. It doesn't have Belady's anomaly. Implementation: track access order using a doubly linked list or, in hardware, use reference bits with the Clock (second-chance) algorithm. OPT (Belady's optimal): evict the page that won't be used for the longest time. This is unrealizable (requires future knowledge) but provides the theoretical lower bound for comparison. LRU is the practical approximation of OPT with good real-world performance.",
     "code": "# Page replacement comparison (reference: 7,0,1,2,0,3,0,4,2,3,0,3 with 3 frames):\n# FIFO: 9 page faults (suffers Belady's anomaly)\n# LRU:  10 page faults\n# OPT:  7 page faults\n#\n# LRU approximation (Clock algorithm):\n# Each page has a reference bit. On fault, scan circularly:\n# if ref_bit=1: clear it, move on\n# if ref_bit=0: evict this page\n# This approximates LRU with minimal hardware support"},

