    {"problem": "Given a string, find the longest palindromic substring. Solve in O(n^2) time and O(1) space.",
     "reasoning": "Expand around center: each palindrome has a center which is either a single character (odd length) or the gap between two characters (even length). There are 2n-1 possible centers. For each center, expand outward while the characters match, tracking the longest palindrome found. The expansion is O(n) per center in the worst case, making total O(n^2). This is simpler and more space-efficient than DP (which is also O(n^2) time but O(n^2) space). For O(n), use Manacher's algorithm which exploits palindrome symmetry to skip redundant expansions, but it's complex to implement correctly.",
     "code": "def longest_palindrome(s):\n    if not s:\n        return ''\n    start = end = 0\n    for i in range(len(s)):\n        for l, r in ((i, i), (i, i+1)):\n            while l >= 0 and r < len(s) and s[l] == s[r]:\n                l -= 1\n                r += 1\n            if r - l - 1 > end - start:\n                start, end = l + 1, r\n    return s[start:end]\n# longest_palindrome('babad') = 'bab' or 'aba'"},

