    {"problem": "Explain the vanishing gradient problem in deep neural networks and how residual connections (ResNet) solve it.",
     "reasoning": "Vanishing gradients occur when gradients become exponentially small as they backpropagate through many layers. In deep networks with sigmoid/tanh activations, the derivative is in (0, 0.25] range — multiplying many such small numbers makes the gradient vanish toward zero, so early layers barely learn. This was a major obstacle to training very deep networks. Residual connections (ResNet) add a skip connection: instead of learning H(x), the layer learns F(x) = H(x) - x, i.e. the residual. The forward pass becomes y = F(x) + x. During backprop, the gradient flows directly through the identity shortcut, bypassing the stacked nonlinear layers. This gives the gradient an 'express lane' to early layers, keeping it from vanishing. ResNet showed that 152-layer networks could be trained effectively, and this principle underlies modern architectures including Transformers (which use pre-norm residual connections for the same reason).",
     "code": "import torch.nn as nn\n\nclass ResidualBlock(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, dim):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.net = nn.Sequential(\n            nn.Linear(dim, dim),\n            nn.ReLU(),\n            nn.Linear(dim, dim),\n        )\n    def forward(self, x):\n        return x + self.net(x)  # skip connection\n\n# Without residual: y = f(g(h(x)))\n# With residual:   y = x + f(g(h(x)))\n# Gradient flows directly through +, bypassing f,g,h"},

